{"parse":{"title":"Phulmoni Dasi rape case","pageid":44634540,"revid":786200925,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Phulmoni Dasi rape case</b> was a case of <a href=\"/wiki/Child_marriage\" title=\"Child marriage\">child marriage</a> and subsequent <a href=\"/wiki/Marital_rape\" title=\"Marital rape\">marital rape</a> in India in 1889, which resulted in the death of the 10-year-old girl, Phulmoni Dasi.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Bannerji2001_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Bannerji2001-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The case led to the conviction of the husband in 1890 and triggered several legal reforms.<sup id=\"cite_ref-CoronilSkurski2006_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CoronilSkurski2006-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Events\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Events</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Trial\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Trial</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Reforms\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Reforms</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Events\">Events</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phulmoni_Dasi_rape_case&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Events\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Phulmoni Dasi was a ten-year-old Bengali girl with a 30-year-old husband named Hari Mohan Maiti. She died after having sexual intercourse with her husband.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Bannerji2001_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Bannerji2001-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Smith2008_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Smith2008-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Sreenivas2008_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sreenivas2008-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Trial\">Trial</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phulmoni_Dasi_rape_case&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Trial\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The case went to trial in the Calcutta Sessions Court on 6 July 1890.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sinha1995_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sinha1995-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The girl's mother provided testimony against the husband.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sreenivas2008_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sreenivas2008-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The husband was convicted under Section 338 of the <a href=\"/wiki/Indian_Penal_Code\" title=\"Indian Penal Code\">Indian Penal Code</a> for \"causing grievous hurt by act endangering life or personal safety of others\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-CoronilSkurski2006_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CoronilSkurski2006-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Under an exception clause in Section 375 of the Indian Penal Code, introduced in 1860, sex with one's own wife was not considered as rape.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sinha1995_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sinha1995-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> As Phulmoni was of legal age and married to Maiti, he was sentenced to 12 months of hard labor.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sreenivas2008_4-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sreenivas2008-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The case is known as <i>Empress v. Hari Mohan Maiti</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Smith2008_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Smith2008-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reforms\">Reforms</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phulmoni_Dasi_rape_case&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Reforms\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>On 9 January 1891, the <a href=\"/wiki/Viceroy_of_India\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Viceroy of India\">Viceroy of India</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Henry_Petty-Fitzmaurice,_5th_Marquess_of_Lansdowne\" title=\"Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 5th Marquess of Lansdowne\">Lord Lansdowne</a> presented a bill before the <a href=\"/wiki/Council_of_India\" title=\"Council of India\">Council of India</a>, which was then headed by <a href=\"/wiki/Andrew_Scoble\" title=\"Andrew Scoble\">Andrew Scoble</a>, called the \"Age of Consent\". It sought to amend Section 376 of the <a href=\"/wiki/Indian_Penal_Code\" title=\"Indian Penal Code\">Indian Penal Code</a>. Previously, the age of consent had been set at 10 in 1860. After the bill was passed on 29 March 1891, the Section 376 included sex with a girl under 12 even if the person is the wife of the perpetrator, as rape.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Bannerji2001_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Bannerji2001-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Phulmoni_Dasi_rape_case&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Bannerji2001-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Bannerji2001_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Bannerji2001_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Bannerji2001_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Himani Bannerji (2001). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=OLyDd5QvDd4C&amp;pg=PA75\"><i>Inventing Subjects: Studies in Hegemony, Patriarchy and Colonialism</i></a>. Anthem Press. pp.&#160;74\u201376. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-84331-073-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-84331-073-0\">978-1-84331-073-0</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">8 December</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Inventing+Subjects%3A+Studies+in+Hegemony%2C+Patriarchy+and+Colonialism&amp;rft.pages=74-76&amp;rft.pub=Anthem+Press&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-84331-073-0&amp;rft.au=Himani+Bannerji&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DOLyDd5QvDd4C%26pg%3DPA75&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APhulmoni+Dasi+rape+case\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-CoronilSkurski2006-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-CoronilSkurski2006_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-CoronilSkurski2006_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Fernando Coronil; Julie Skurski (2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=Ftne6Ezh5aAC&amp;pg=PA417\"><i>States of Violence</i></a>. University of Michigan Press. p.&#160;417. <a href=\"/wiki/Intern